Parliament has not ratified the amendment for the release of Tymosenko
The Ukrainian parliament refused, in the context of an amendment to criminal law, the draft annulment of the paragraph relating to the indictment of Julia Tymosenko, the leader of the opposition.
The second reading of the draft amendment to reduce penalties for economic offences, which could have opened the doors of freedom for the former Prime Minister currently in prison, was rejected by Members of Parliament.
Tymosenko was sentenced in October to 7 years in prison for having concluded a priori disadvantageous agreement with Russia for the purchase of natural gas.
The judgment is not final and the court is to decide on the appeal of the convicted person in December.
Tymosenko qualifies the judgment of political revenge of the regime and has caused a process of suspicions of bias of the court also to the west.
The draft annulment of paragraph 365 of criminal law, on the basis of which the former Prime Minister was sentenced, was signed by 147 deputies.
It would have taken 226 votes to approve.
