How travel prices have changed since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
The travel agencies at that time offered trips mainly in the countries of the socialist bloc, because travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists traveled for holidays in East Germany, Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea and Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A great exception for the period from 1962 to 1972 when he was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia and then the regime began to have a western inclination and travel to Yugoslavia were very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not allowed for the citizens of the socialist bloc (also for the Czechoslovaks) to travel individually even within the framework of the socialist countries.
If the Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel individually, for example in Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter or the individual journey was not authorized.
Travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the west, however, it was necessary to queue all night with a sleeping bag or have a "good knowledge" within the travel agency.
And even after that it wasn't yet won.
The agreement for currencies which was the condition for traveling to the west was denied to people "politically incorrect" who could not travel at all.
However, the Czechoslovak currency was not interchangeable and it was not possible to obtain financial resources without the currency agreement (Western currency) to travel to the west.
The Czechs spent most of their vacations in the country where there were therefore many country houses and cottages that the Czechs bought and this habit lasted until now.
Czech travel has since experienced a great revolution in 1989.
Although until 1989 the holiday in East Germany and Bulgaria was at most, Czechs spent last year abroad 4 million vacation days in countries around the world.
The great paradox we are not aware of today is that the most popular country is Croatia where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 because part of Yugoslavia at the time.
The removal of visas in the 1990s in neighbouring western countries caused a huge wave of short-term visits especially in Austria in Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks were not able to travel by plane to the west for a long time that everyone wanted to see at least one moment.
For example, in Paris travel organizations made Czechs sleep in tents in parks because our revenues did not allow us to pay for the hotel or a pension.
The typical feature of a Czech trip was at this time to take with itself its own canned food, sausage, etc... to save money.
Another important moment was also the interchangeability of the Czech crown which finally allowed our tourists after decades of freely buying Western currency.
Our standard of living and the average wage have increased what caused another important moment in 1997.
Thanks to a growing demand for travel travel, travel agencies have begun since 1997 to prepare tours with air charter links that have greatly reduced the costs compared to what was before.
By the end of the 1990s, Czechs had visa-free links with virtually most developed countries around the world except the EU which later facilitated our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolution tourism, when the first air charter was prepared to an exotic country, Thailand, from the Czech Republic.
Since this year and every year direct air charters have taken Czech tourists to the far hot countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
More than 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolution development arrived in 2008.
on 17 November 2008, the EU abolished visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to settle completely in the group of developed countries.
In 2008, also Czechs for the first time in history spent more than half of their vacation abroad (50, 3%) and for the first time in history spent more than 15,000 kroner per person for vacation abroad, including attached charges.
