The low temperatures in February, apart from causing trillion losses for the agricultural sector, have limited the opportunities of the state economy for growth, caused a contraction of economic activity in general by 3.6% in the first half of the year, mainly justified by the historic fall of 31.16 per cent in agriculture, which has affected the dynamism of the other economic sectors.
According to the report of freezings from the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, there have been damage of 582 million 835 hectares cultivated, of which 78.03 per cent have suffered total damage and the rest of 21.07 per cent have suffered partial damage, the main crops were vegetables, maize and peas.
The decline in economic activity generated, until November, a steady rise in unemployment in the State, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, the State's unemployment rate during the first three quarters of the year, an accelerated increase was observed, as, from January to March, 55 thousand 053 signals were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 per cent of the Active Economic Population, the rate in the second quarter became 5.28 per cent and from July to September the average continued to rise to 6.19 per cent, a rate representing more than 74 thousand unemployed signals, an increase compared to the first half of 18 thousand 969 people.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, according to economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, rising unemployment can be explained indirectly by public policy actions.
"What is observed is an increase in unemployment due to various factors, including the loss of liquidity on the market due to a restriction of resources approved by the legislation in Congress to combat money-laundering, because for people who make dollars in an illegal way it is not easy for them to work to earn them, invest them and use them in something," he said.
Migration in custody
López Cervantes reported that the increase in unemployment is also due to a demographic factor.
"The number of people who leave the state to go to work abroad, in the United States has been restricted, first because of the difficulties of entry and second because they already have a lot of difficulty in finding work, these people remain here and ask for sources of work, which makes unemployment rise," he said.
Serious absence
The analysis of the labour market is worsening by considering the high level of serious lack of conditions that prevail between the working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 per cent of the population employed in that state works there without contributing as a worker in any social insurance institution.
Apart from unemployment and the lack of serious benefits, another reason for disengagement for the state is low wages, the entity has lower pay in the country, according to the registers of the Mexican Institute of Social Insurance and the Secretariat of Labour and Social Security.
The average monthly income of signal workers was, until September, 5 thousand 352 pesos, well below the national average, which is 7 thousand 375 pesos.
IED Contraction
Apart from the decrease in economic activity and the rise in unemployment, in 2011 the highest reduction in the Direct Foreign Investment over the past 10 years was recorded, according to the Economic Secretariat from January to June, the State FDI reached $630 thousand 697, representing a decrease of 87.74 per cent compared to the $5 million 143 thousand 312 recorded in the same period of the previous year.
In turn, the Economic Development Secretariat of the Government of the State accounts for a total investment of 17,280 billion pesos per year, mainly registered by the tertiary sector companies.
Debt
Given the economic contraction scenario, in July the Government of the State requested approval of a 3 trillion pesos credit for investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, with the aim of reactivating the economy, approval of the state congress was 2,600 billion pesos and until November no debt benefits were observed in any sector of the state economy.
Reactions
For employers' representatives, the first year of Government of Mario López Valdés demonstrates a lack of government management capacity.
Miguel Loredo López, President of the National Chamber of the Transformation Industry, said that in 2011 there was no harmonization of the will of the various sectors, including the Government of the State.
"The performance of the Sinaloa economy during this year has been really very poor, it is necessary to work intensively to recover the land we lost this year, in 2012 we need to double our efforts, it has been necessary to align the effort of all and especially the good already synchronized walk of this new government team, hopefully the next year will be much better," he said.
Economic slow
Loredo López stated that events such as the early freezing of the year have retained the state economy and have restricted its performance and growth.
"The low economic flow is produced by several events, including ice cream, one of the main effects has been a slow economy which does not turn fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows for an acceptable level and flow in trials, products and services and, therefore, at the end of the year, we close much below the expectations that we had," he said.
Redefine vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Oriarte, President of the Patronal Confederation of the Mexican Republic of Sinaloa, said that we want to channel the state into productive activities of more dynamism.
"In general terms we have observed that we have worked, we believe it is necessary to develop a long-term programme that redefines the vocation and economic direction of the state, because it is important that we have the full potential of the material and human resources of Sinaloa," he said.
A lot to do
The President of Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision for the future that would better channel the Government's efforts.
"In general terms, I would say that the Government has made efforts to achieve good results in various areas, in terms of economic development, there are some progress, but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown progress in the management of public policy.
"There are elements that allow us to say that the Government is more inclusive, what I can say is that much has been done and the Government is aware of the fact that there is still much to be done," he said.
