The Court valid "analog cut" in Mexico in 2015
Replacement of analog signals by digital is one of the most important changes the world has suffered in recent years
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) rejected the constitutional disputes that the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies have formulated against the presidential decree that advances the so-called "analog cupour" from 2021 to 2015, as the eight votes necessary to invalidate it have not been gathered.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers when he issued the decree detailing the actions to be taken to implement the transition to digital terrestrial television.
With this result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic has been put down for failing to reach the qualified majority of eight votes so that the Court can decide on the constitutionality or non-constitutionality of the decree, and this continues to be in force.
The draft award, prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed the decree's declaration as non-constitutional, because the regulation on radio and television is a statutory assignment reserved for the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in violation of the principles of hierarchical subordination and reserve of law.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted in favour of the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies have promoted two constitutional disputes to challenge the decree and to admit complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions planned by it for the digital transition.
The plenary meeting of the Ministers also resolved to dismiss the complaint made by the Chamber of Deputies, without discussing the project that Minister Sánchez Cordero is also responsible for.
In his speech, the Minister said that he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the Federal Executive cannot structure through general standards the measures for the preparation of the project.
"I also consider that if I did so, the autonomy of the regulatory body would be affected," he recalled that planning public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the Federal Executive, who has the constitutional mandate of the government.
Replacement of analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has suffered in recent years and this results in better exploitation of radio spectrum, better quality of signal and more channels.
Adjournment of change, he argued, would be to postpone the benefits of digitalisation which implies a decision of public interest which not only has a technical dimension, "because it also includes economic, social, political and national security issues".
These questions, he stressed, "require the operation of a whole system, which, in accordance with the principle of economic direction of the State, includes a group of powers which the Constitution grants to the faculty of the Executive of the State."
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the digital transition and they have done so through the Executive, despite the fact that they had highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, by issuing the contested decree, has invaded the sphere of competence of Congress in a form, as it ensures in the administrative sphere that the laws issued by the legislature are respected.
An analysis of the possibility of a vote-by-voting count in Michoacán
According to the data highlighted by PREP, the difference between the first and second place of the Governor's election is only 27 per cent, even without accounting for the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total verbatim records.
The possibility of "vote-by-vote" counting is a reality with regard to the electoral trial this year in Michoacán, where according to the data highlighted by the Preliminary Election Results Program (PREP) the difference between the first and second place of the governor's election is only 27 percent, even without accounting for the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total verbatim records.
In this regard, the President of the General Council of the Institut Electoral de Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, on November 9, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines to harmonize local standards with federal electoral reform.
It will be recalled that Michoacán has not approved either its Constitution or its Electoral Code of State or its Electoral Justice Act, at the same time that the Congress of the State has approved the reforms shortly before the legal deadline for this electoral trial to enter into force and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel has omitted his publication within the time limit provided for by the Law of the Official Journal of the State, with the argument that he had a few objections.
On 9 November, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional controversy promoted by the Local Legislative Power and qualified as "invalid and illegal" the vote of the state agent for constitutional reforms, as he does not have the right to "sanction or contest them".
Interviewed on the possibility of "vote by vote", María de los Ángeles Llanderal said that thanks to the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the General Council of IEM it will be possible to carry out the partial and total counts of votes by the local electoral body.
Thus, the partial count of votes, one or more electoral packages, may be that: the results of the minutes do not match; there is no polling report and the ballot file does not appear in the ballot box; or there are obvious errors or alterations in the minutes.
In addition, the total count of votes received in all election ballots may be made when there is an indication that the difference between the alleged candidate winning the respective election and the one who obtained the second place in the election is equal or below a percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the session there is an express petition by the party representative and/or coalition who presented the second one of the candidates reported.
The total count of the vote may also be held if at the end of the joint count it turns out that the difference between the alleged winning candidate and that of the second place is equal to or less than a percentage point, provided that there is an express petition by the representative of the political party whose candidate has emerged second, in which case the electoral packages that were subject to the partial counting will be excluded.
It should be mentioned that this is the situation of the election of Morelia, where according to the PREP, the difference between the first and second place is only 0.16 percent, even without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total minutes.
