The designated Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet with the President of Italy on Wednesday to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on board the economic disaster and put the whole Eurozone at risk.
A press release from the Presidential Palace announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, would meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm that he can form the Government.
It is expected that he will present a cabinet composed of technocrats in his majority, even if it is unclear when the new executive takes office.
Monti said he was going to present to the president the outcome of his talks with the political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," said the former European Commissioner for Journalists.
Monti did not explicitly say that he could form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles had been overcome.
The frame is now well-drawn, he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, at a shorter time than normally, while Italy is fighting a political and financial crisis that has increased its debt costs to levels that cannot be supported.
The new administration led by the former European Commissioner Monti must approve a tough austerity package required by European leaders to regain confidence in Italy that had been affected.
By stressing the pressure on Monti to move forward, the instability of the markets to place the performance of the Italian BTP bonds at 10 years above 7 per cent, the level at which Greece and Ireland had been saved.
