"We believe Professor Monti's efforts will have a good result," said Angelino Alfano, secretary of the right-wing party.
The support of PDL, the largest Italian party, is significant because so far many of its members have opposed the Government of the majority technocrat that Monti forms.
Parliamentary support
The new Monti government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what will likely be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blocking or delay in his efforts could lead to a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks has added to the pressure by observing that a bankruptcy in Monti would be a disaster.
Monti began consultations with political parties, trade unions and employers' groups and youth and women's organizations on Monday.
He'll finish his meeting tour Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, which enabled an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief rest at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi was going to resign, the costs of Italian debt were now returned to critical levels between uncertainty about the success of the new Prime Minister.
Saving Italy, with a public debt of 1.9 billion euros, would be too much for the current financial defences of Eurozone.
