Seeing the tour, you have offered huge shows, with many songs.
What have you planned for your presentation in Costa Rica?
As we have never produced there, we have no restrictions on what we can do.
We will try to make the best show possible, with a wide variety of songs; we will try to interpret two songs from each album and offer our fans a good and diverse directory.
You never repeat the directory.
What do you owe it to?
I think it's partly because we have nine discs and we can play more than 120 songs and everyone loves different songs, that's why it's very difficult to choose which songs to play every night.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we have not interpreted for a very long time, it helps us to stay focused and surprises us because it reminds us why we love these songs and that we may have forgotten.
This makes the show more interesting for us and therefore I think it becomes also more interesting for people.
With this tour, you celebrate 20 years of trajectory.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything you've done?
Yes, absolutely.
First of all, I believe that none of us had imagined that we were going to form a large rock group, and the fact that we did it for more than 20 years makes it seem like a dream.
We continue to tell our blessings and the fact that we can continue to make music together makes us very excited.
We love and love to create music.
We're lucky to go to places in the world we've always wanted to go to.
Things couldn't be better for us.
What does it mean for you to have been a fundamental element in the creation of the grunt?
It has always been an honour for us to be part of this group of great groups.
We are very friends with people from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising when a movement arises from a group of friends and is uncommon.
From time to time, a group emerges from a city, but it is much more strange when five or ten groups leave at the same time from the same city.
We are proud and it is an honor for us to be part of Seattle's group.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year we attended a festival with Alice in Chains and we went to Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on their tour, so we're lucky to be still friends with all of them and it's an honor for us to be part of that Seattle sound that arose.
It's also very strange that a group like yours stays together and with the same members for so long.
Yes, four of us were together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, and only this is much longer than many groups normally last.
First of all, I believe that we are all lucky enough to be still alive and, secondly, we are all concerned about others.
We are all close friends and thanks to this there are musical boulevards that give everyone freedom to experiment.
We trust each other with each other's music and that could not be better.
Your relationship with the word celebrity has not been easy; however, thanks to your success, you have been able to do whatever you want.
How do you find a balance?
As we grew up, it was easier for us to find a balance.
We make sure that we don't spend too much time on tour because it's easy to fall into this game of great crowds and people who love your music.
If we don't forget that people are here for music, it helps us not to forget that we have to respect music and what it has brought, without taking into account the fact that we are famous and a rock star, which doesn't really interest any of us.
How do you remember your other project, Mother Love Bone?
