The Mexican Institute of Social Insurance (IMSS) announced that it conducts an investigation to discover the gene of obesity in the case of children and young people, known as the "Genetics of the Obesity of Children and Adolescents" protocol that will allow the markers associated with overweight.
In a press release, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Specialities Hospital of the National Medical Centre of the 20th Century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been formed.
This team is supported by specialists and third-cycle students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Advanced Research and Studies (Cinvesav) from the National Polytechnic Institute (INP).
The investigation calls for participation of the population with or without the right to participate in the participating sports units of the IMSS in the Valley of Mexico, where evidence to minors is made every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol began in the sports unit Cuauhtémoc (State of Mexico West) and that as of 8 October, the activity took place in the sports unit of Nezahualcoyolt (State of Mexico East).
After reaching the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 minors, the study will continue in the Independencia Sports Unit (south of Federal District) and finally in Morelos Sports Unit (north of Federal District).
He explained that the objective of this investigation and the objective of this research is to identify the components and the importance of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and young people to prevent chronic degenerative diseases.
As will be celebrated on 14 November on World Diabetes Day, he mentioned that the goal is to bring together three thousand children and young people between six and 14 years of age, with the consent and under the supervision of their parents, to apply specific food questionnaires.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and history of family inheritance of their diseases, to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that Saturdays will be applied to all participants in anthropometric measurements (weight, size, size circumference), blood pressure, glucose levels determination, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin and genetics (one seeks to identify people associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López reported that this investigation is the result of the concern of health professionals for alarming weight gain in the case of minors.
'The 1999 and 2006 health surveys reported that in just six years, there has been an increase, in the case of boys, of 77 per cent obesity and in the case of girls of 47 per cent; in the case of overweight, there has also been a dramatic increase', said the IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the population of the country is different from the others by its genetic history.
He informed that on average, Mexicans have 65 per cent of indo-American inheritance, 30 per cent European and five per cent African, and this condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn the excess energy consumed (calories), which is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for participants is the full evaluation of children, which enables them to detect if they have a degree of overweight or obesity.
He even said that the presence of dark-colored folds (acanthosis) on the neck and forearms indicate the probability of having metabolic and even pre-diabetes alterations.
The information is managed in a confidential manner, and the doctors hand it over in writing to the parents, to whom each is explained of the measures and changes in the lifestyle they have to achieve in order to prevent diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentaryism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, stay most of the day sitting in front of the TV and use means of transport instead of walking on short distances.
Another cause is the high caloric intake, i.e. the highest consumption of sweet drinks, carbohydrates (tamals - meat pasta to cornmeal wrapped in corn leaves - bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and the genetics analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM's asphalt would prevent cassis
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signs that the paved were resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair approximately 200 thousand cases each rainy season in the Metropolitan Zone of the Valley of Mexico, alert Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who ensured that if the process of construction and maintenance of the bituminous pavement is adequate, the cassis could be reduced or even eliminated completely.
During his conference A technological opinion on cassis, organized within the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory he is responsible for develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some northern cities, to improve the performance, and therefore, the formation of cassis.
He explained that asphalt, the heavier part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphalts, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called malthenes, which together give the pâté its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behaviour of the asphalt consists in the fact that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, behaves like a liquid, 120 degrees C its viscosity is very large and at 50 degrees C it presents an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes breaking, adds.
This means that in the streets the resistance of asphalt is not uniform and changes during the day depending on the environmental and temperature conditions, warns the specialist in chemical engineering.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Ciudad de México mostly were covered by a flexible pavement, consisting of six layers of materials, the last three involving asphalt.
Among the more superficial layers is the layer of asphalt, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and subsequently compacted.
Each of the small stones that forms the layer, he pointed out, is bathed year asphalt.
When vehicles go through it with efforts, it allows the forces to propagate very well in the pavement.
If we had modified asphalt, they would spread better, the chemical engineer thought.
On the asphalt layer, he said, one last layer called the rolling layer, made of fine stone, that is, sand which is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer in contact with the wheels of vehicles, it must have more mechanical force than the asphalt layer and provide adhesion on the street.
As the part of the Pavé receives and distributes the efforts, the rolling layer also requires that the Pavé has adequate thickness and the material it is made must be treated.
The climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, is also a very important factor to consider, especially water, as they significantly affect the yield of the asphalt layer.
When the soil becomes wet, the water spreads inside the layer, it is difficult to do so, which collapses all the layers of the pavement and therefore causes the cassis.
In the process of forming a cassia, he said, the first one that breaks down is the rolling film and only later is affected the asphalt layer, but the damage does not take place immediately, but it is a process that needs to be treated at the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National Research System explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor in the formation of cassia and therefore the thickness of each layer of the pavement must always be linked to the load of vehicles and ensure its satisfaction, in order to avoid frequent formation of cassia.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still a lot to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, bituminous emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and allow for easy and without having to use high temperatures.
