Thus was the work of the person of Cali who identified the body of Alfonso Cano
A dactyloscopicist from Cali went on to history like the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials is crucial.
On November 4th, a keyographer of the Cali ITC went through history as the person who confirmed the identity of the Supreme Leader of the Farcs: "Alfonso Cano", comparing his fingerprints.
Of the seven dactyloscopicists working at the local ITC offices, this week was the "availability" tour of Elias González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working in the field of judicial investigation for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in the municipalities of Chocó, where he often had to spend more than five days in the forest to get to the place where the bodies were to be identified.
In 2000, he moved to the capital of Valle and, after following proper courses, he specialized in dactyloscopy, which is the study of friction skin, i.e. palms and feet.
During the week of the operation against alias Alfonso Cano we warned Elias to take clothes with him for at least three days.
Something very big was waiting for him.
On Friday night he left for Cauca in a Palmira helicopter.
He knew that he had to identify two bodies and that one of them was suspected to be the man who was leading the oldest guerrilla in the world, so he was asked to take the card with the ten fingerprints of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
But when he arrived with the investigation team at the site of the body, he did not recognize it by its physical aspect, because it was very different from the one he had seen in the media.
He had no beard, he was dressed like a peasant in the area, without glasses and much thinner.
But fingerprints don't lie.
Accompanied by a galtonian magnifying glass, ink, picker and lantern, Elias compared the fingerprints of the body with those of the map.
His eye was not mistaken: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was responsible who confirmed to the Minister of Defence, Juan Carlos Pinzón that yes, he was the supreme chief of the Farcs.
Looking for the print
For a Dactyloscopicist of Sijín de Cali the recognition that President Juan Manuel Santos made to Elias González, in a press conference for the operation against "Cano", is very significant.
Many people don't know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an accurate science, without margin of error, which can be crucial in the resolution of crimes.
Apart from identifying the bodies, the dactyloscopicists support investigations into crimes such as theft and homicide and confirm the identity of the captured persons.
When captured, many offenders present false identity cards or do not have any documents.
We take their fingerprints and search them in the database.
The researcher said that in a flight case he had to remove part of a wall from a house, because in this place the thief had held his hand to get out a safe full of jewelry and money.
"The walls are difficult because they are not adequate surfaces to draw a fingerprint, but in this case we were able to get the fingerprint of all hands and identify the offender who had participated in different flights," he recalls.
The fingerprints may also remove or confirm suspects in cases of homicide.
Recently we found a dead man with bottles of drink around him.
By means of the investigation it was determined that a parent could be suspected of the crime and indeed a fingerprint on the bottle coincided.
Even if it doesn't guarantee he's the killer, it's the crime scene.
One ITC dactyloscopicist explained that "digital fingerprints are extracted from objects with chemical or physical reagents".
When they appear, a pick-up or a band is used to remove them.
Subsequently, fingerprints are sent to Asif, the trigger database, or to the National Civil Registry.
"The problem is that there are still many undocumented Colombians," said the CTI expert.
He explained that everything is not how we show up in the CSI television program.
As all that shines is not gold, anything that touches does not necessarily become a fingerprint.
It can, however, be used if the necessary confrontation is made.
