Japan was born after the earthquake
GDP increases by 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and ends the downward spiral in early March
Since March, the Japanese economy has been paralyzed, still conquering after the devastating earthquake that has become a nuclear crisis, the worst disaster in the country of Japan since the Second World War.
The first estimates of the Government of Tokyo calculated the material losses at $300 million, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, seemed to have diminished.
After three consecutive trimesters of falls, the data of the Gross Domestic Product between July and September used to turn the page permanently: GDP increased 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and 6% in annualized rates.
The second quarter - for the Japanese, the fiscal year starts in March 2012 - also assumes the highest rate of increase from January to March 2010.
The recovery is partly due to the resumption of acquisitions of equipment to restore areas devastated by the earthquake and the subsequent tsunami.
In fact, companies increased their investments by 1.1%, compared to the decrease of 0.9% of the capital expenditure observed from January to March, the first decline after six months of unabated increase.
However, the real stimulus of the Japanese economy is not based solely on the Keynesian impulse that invites us to take advantage of the crisis to consolidate - or rebuild - infrastructures, use deficiencies for zero growth.
Japan has mainly woken up by changing domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japan's GDP.
This variable has grown by 1%, driven by increased spending on vehicles, travel and entertainment activities.
