Legalize euthanasia and assisted suicide, says an expert committee
Canadians live in denial of death, according to the report of the Royal Society of Canada
With regard to palliative care, the committee calls for governments, health care institutions, and physicians to work together to ensure better palliative care, beyond cancer cases.
Canadian society lives in denial of death.
Only 9% of Canadians agree to speak with their doctor about the conditions under which they want to die and make arrangements to do so.
This is one of the conclusions of a strong report by the Royal Society of Canada, involving six experts related to various fields, including ethics, law and medicine.
This committee recommends that the Government amend the Criminal Code so as to allow assisted suicide and euthanasia, where necessary, with a patient deemed competent to make such a decision.
At the start of the game, experts cite a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit, which compared the quality of death in 40 countries on the planet.
If Canada has ranked 10th, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has generated a culture in which people fear to address the subject of death."
Medicalization or not, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, report to us the experts mandated by the Royal Society of Canada.
And despite the desire that most Canadians die at home, 68.6% end up dying at the hospital.
Overall, in Quebec, this rate is the highest, with 86% of the deaths occurring in the hospital.
On the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report come to conclusions that go against the position of the federal government, which has already said that there is no change in the Criminal Code concerning euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to the experts, who have also reviewed all countries where these approaches are legalized or decriminalized, there is no evidence that this decriminalization leads to abuse in the application, i.e. the practice of euthanasia or suicide assisted by non-competent or non-consensive persons.
On the contrary, he said yesterday in teleconference Jocelyn Downie, co-signator of the report, there would be more cases of these overflows specifically in countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are not legalized.
"Euthanasia is practised in Canada, where it is clearly illegal."
"The assisted suicide is practiced in Canada, where it is clearly illegal," says Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians in favour of euthanasia
We recall that 85% of Canadians have already voted in favour of euthanasia because they believe it would allow people at the end of their lives to alleviate their suffering, according to a 2010 Angus Reid survey.
And 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia will not have the effect of sending the message that the life of the elderly or disabled is less valuable.
As for persons who have committed assisted suicide, 41% of the respondents felt that they should not be prosecuted.
With regard to the maintenance or cessation of care with a patient, the situation is less clear, the authors of the report say.
Therefore, in the list of their recommendations, they suggest that it is indicated in the Criminal Code that the withdrawal of care for which there has been a legally valid refusal is not criminal.
The Committee of Experts also calls for health professionals to be trained to respect life-long care refusal without fear of criminal prosecution.
With regard to palliative care, the committee calls for governments, health care institutions, and physicians to work together to ensure better palliative care, beyond cancer cases.
Finally, with regard to palliative or terminal sedation, which is already widely used in Canadian health institutions, the committee requests that it be considered, when it does not serve to reduce physical pain, such as euthanasia, and to be subject to the same procedures.
Reserves of other experts
Some health law experts have already made reservations regarding the findings of the Royal Society of Canada's report.
Pierre Deschamps, a specialist in health law, has qualified as "extreme" the position of the signatory experts of the report, among other things because it does not limit the practice of euthanasia to the terminally ill.
"It opens the door to a situation where everyone who would be tired of life and who would be over 18 could ask for help to commit suicide," said Deschamps, who had consulted a summary of the report yesterday.
