The North Stream, a new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The North Stream gas pipeline, directly linking Western Europe to Russia, moving to the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has entered into service.
It must provide gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with a burst.
More than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, participated last Tuesday on the Baltic shores, between orchestras and fine buffets, at the inauguration of the North Stream, this new gas pipeline that connects Russia directly, under the sea, to Germany.
Symbolicly, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte turned together the wheel of the valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, 27.5 billion cubic metres of additional Russian gas will arrive each year in Western Europe by a first 1,224 km tube linking the St. Petersburg region to the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second tube must be completed at the end of 2012, enabling a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, equivalent to all French consumption.
And we already mention the possibility of building a third on the same route.
For Gazprom, the completion in time and time of this huge construction site has the air of victory.
The project had been strongly challenged by Poland and the Baltic countries.
The North Stream will be able to deliver gas directly to Germany, avoiding any land crossing through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
As a result, these two countries lose some of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw had not hesitated to compare the North Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is whether the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security of its supplies.
But it is at the cost of a weakening of Europe of energy, as the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has barely succeeded in having its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which are heavily gas users, and whose deposits are declining.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that binds us organically," François Filon confirmed by opening this pipeline, demonstrating to what extent the major gas contracts are both political and economic.
All of this explains the broad smiles displayed by Gazprom's leaders, present in number in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical operation.
The underwater tube is made of concrete-gained steel to protect it against ships' anchorages.
It is located on the seabed, 200 m on average.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid fields of mines dating from the Second World War.
"A hundred must have been removed or destroyed, by precaution," said Jens Müller, spokesperson for North Stream.
There was also a need to multiply the measures to protect wildlife and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake, heavy like 242 Eiffel towers, that nothing interrupts on its entire length: no valve, no maintenance station.
A control platform was planned across Sweden, but project managers gave up while the Swedish were reluctant to see a Russian state society established on a permanent basis off their coast.
"In case of damage, we stop the gas passage in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas contained in the gas pipeline shall therefore escape into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the manufacturers who planned the welds to escape every 100,000 years.
Monitoring of the state of the pipeline shall be carried out by an underwater robot, drawn by a vessel, for external observation, as well as by an aircraft operating inside the pipeline.
Of the shape of a cigar, it is introduced inside the tube, width of one meter diameter, and it is pushed by the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at the speed of 3 meters second, it provides accurate information on possible metal deformations.
The gas pipeline was designed to run fifty years without having to suffer the least repair.
Gas circulation is simply ensured by pressure.
It's 200 bars from the start, and 100 bars from the start.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, who keeps 51% of the shares.
The Germans E.ON and BASF were joined (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have established a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for building and operating the pipeline.
She has her seat in Zoug, Switzerland, where the tax is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased to this company, for twenty renewable years, all of the gas transport capabilities.
" Gazprom will pay for total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported," says Jens Müller.
Funding for gas pipeline construction was provided at 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work is expected to reach EUR 7.4 billion for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment has risen to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to return to their costs, as only Gazprom takes the risk.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic to Lubmin, on a sandy coast planted with pines.
Valves, 4,5 meters tall, form the gas outlet door.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificities of the gas that comes before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since Tuesday, this terminal receives one million cubic metres of Russian gas every hour that passes.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
Moleskine, brand name card.
Created about 15 years ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to give the taste of writing.
It has a scent of adventures, hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular cover, its elastic, its leaves of a broken white colour, as old as by time.
Yet, the Moleskine booklet as we know it today was born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided to launch a design notebook but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, is responsible for the launch of the new product.
The notebook is based on an old production technique, the mole skin (skin skin) which means a varnished cotton used to cover banquets for example.
This type of booklet was very popular with writers and travelers.
" Moleskine gave to the taste of the day an old and forgotten object, which was an icon of the avant-garde artists, up to the twentieth century ", says Maria Sebregondi, who has become the brand leader at Modo Modo.
Success is here.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to 12.7 million coins.
We are far from the confidential production of the first years, where only 3,000 books were designed.
Moleskine exceeds the Italian borders and exports to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to establish a robot portrait of the buyer, as the notebook seduces both the businessman and the student and the professionals.
Like Moleskine, its consumers are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultivated.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees at its beginnings, accounts for almost 100 today and has since 2008 two offices; one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her books in the bookstores, from Fnac to small downtown shops and has been able to impose her identity.
"We have followed the air of time and this new need for writing, despite the rise of emails," says Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies Moleskine's development: the brand recently launched an exhibition "Detour " where architects or artists exhibit their own books.
In August, she also launched a leopard cover, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and its cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, agendas, pens, computer covers... The brand features a wide range of media.
A success that made ambitions: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in Moleskine's history.
Why does the unemployment rate of disabled workers remain so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th week for the employment of disabled people opens today.
Despite a voluntary public policy in 2005, the unemployment rate of persons with disabilities is even twice as high as the average: 19%, compared with 9% for the whole population.
Discouragement?
"No, says Éric Blanchet, Director General of the Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of persons with disabilities."
" The progress made over the past 15 years has been considerable. "
"At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher."
"However, there is still a great deal to be done."
It must be said that for the disabled, there are still many barriers to access to employment.
They are fairly old: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have the scholarship and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread: 53% for people with disabilities, compared to 38% on average.
In short, so many criteria that specifically complicate return to employment, and which "are the core of the problem", according to Christian Grapin, Director General of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
This is for objective brakes.
It remains the non-said, the mentality that evolves, of course, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Enterprise Association for the City indicated that the interviewed managers have "a low level of knowledge of disability ", with a "overrepresentation of people in wheelchairs, psychic or intellectual disabilities " .
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from reaching the employment target of 6% of disabled workers, as set out in a law of... 1987.
The last known figures, which date back to 2008, show a ratio of 2.6%.
"We are now around 3%," said Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the organization responsible for collecting the contributions of companies that do not comply with this law.
The evidence: the number of "taxed" establishments, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59 000 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
" The 2005 Law, which increased contributions, created strong pressure on companies," explained Pierre Blanc.
" But this improvement also reflects real awareness, especially in large groups. "
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared with 82% of businesses from 100 to 199 employees.
